<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-269-868  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 269 868.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  Jan 15 1990 v4 n2 p22(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Messaging systems. (Tech Briefing)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Taylor, Kymberly.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Electronic messaging has come of age in the federal government asadvances in networks and messaging software, along with the pushfor standardization of data interchange systems, encourage thecreation of a unified messaging environment.andP;  Government spendingon electronic mail grew from $38.9 million in 1985 to $139.4million in 1988.andP;  Growth is expected to continue.andP;  The size of thefederal bureaucracy makes it ideal for electronic mail, voice mailand other automated messaging applications.andP;  Government agencieshave adapted the technology to boost productivity, assure accuracyand save time and money.andP;  Industry analysts say that if theFederal Telecommunications System 2000 program is successful itwill speed up interconnectivity among federal systems and triggerinnovations in areas such as speech recognition, speech synthesisand automatic foreign language translation.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Communications TechnologyElectronic Mail SystemsVoice MailTrendsConnectivityGovernmentCommunications Industry.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>